            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this sugar intake calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates a
                <strong>personalized daily limit for added sugar</strong> using
                public health guidelines and your approximate calorie needs. It
                then compares that limit with the sugar you log from drinks and
                foods.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Estimate your daily calorie needs</h3>
              <p>
                To keep things simple and fast, the calculator uses a
                <strong>weight- and activity-based estimate</strong>
                instead of a full basal metabolic rate equation:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Step 1 – Convert weight to kg (if needed)</strong>
                </p>
                <p>\(\text{weight\_kg} = \text{weight\_lb} / 2.2046\)</p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong
                    >Step 2 – Choose a calories-per-kg factor by
                    activity</strong
                  >
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Sedentary: 28 kcal/kg</li>
                  <li>Lightly active: 30 kcal/kg</li>
                  <li>Moderately active: 33 kcal/kg</li>
                  <li>Very active: 36 kcal/kg</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>Step 3 – Adjust for age group</strong>
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Child (4–12): × 0.95</li>
                  <li>Teen (13–18): × 1.05</li>
                  <li>Adult (19–64): × 1.00</li>
                  <li>Senior (65+): × 0.9</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>Estimated daily calories</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{calories} = \text{weight\_kg} \times
                  \text{activity\_factor} \times \text{age\_factor}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Apply added sugar percentage limits</h3>
              <p>
                Most organizations recommend keeping
                <strong>added sugar below 10% of daily calories</strong>, and
                ideally around 5%. This calculator lets you choose how strict
                you want to be:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>General health:</strong> 10% of calories from added
                  sugar.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Weight loss / metabolic health:</strong> 7.5% of
                  calories.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Heart health / diabetes risk:</strong> 5% of calories.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Step 4 – Sugar calories from percentage</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{sugar\_kcal} = \text{daily\_calories} \times
                  \text{sugar\_percent}\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong
                    >Step 5 – Convert calories to grams and teaspoons</strong
                  >
                </p>
                <p>Each gram of sugar ≈ 4 kcal:</p>
                <p>\(\text{grams} = \text{sugar\_kcal} / 4\)</p>
                <p>1 teaspoon sugar ≈ 4 g:</p>
                <p>\(\text{teaspoons} = \text{grams} / 4\)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Calculate your current intake</h3>
              <p>
                For each drink or food you add, the calculator multiplies
                <strong>servings × grams of sugar per serving</strong>
                and sums everything:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  \(\text{total\_sugar\_g} = \sum (\text{servings}_i \times
                  \text{g\_per\_serving}_i)\)
                </p>
                <p>\(\text{total\_teaspoons} = \text{total\_sugar\_g} / 4\)</p>
                <p>\(\text{total\_kcal} = \text{total\_sugar\_g} \times 4\)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The progress bar shows your
                <strong>percentage of the recommended limit</strong>:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>0–75%:</strong> Green – comfortably within the
                  guideline.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>75–100%:</strong> Yellow – getting close to the upper
                  limit.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>100–150%:</strong> Orange – above the recommended
                  limit.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>150%+:</strong> Red – well above the recommended
                  limit.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>What counts as “added sugar”?</h2>
              <p>
                Added sugar is
                <strong>any sugar that is added to foods or drinks</strong>
                during processing, cooking or at the table. It includes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Table sugar (sucrose), brown sugar, raw sugar.</li>
                <li>High-fructose corn syrup, glucose-fructose syrup.</li>
                <li>Honey, syrups (maple, agave, rice, etc.).</li>
                <li>
                  Sugar added to yogurt, breakfast cereals, sauces, desserts,
                  drinks.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                It <strong>does not necessarily include</strong> naturally
                occurring sugars in:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Whole fruits and vegetables.</li>
                <li>Plain milk and unsweetened dairy products.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These natural sources come with fiber, protein, vitamins and
                minerals, which change how your body handles the sugar. Most
                health guidelines focus on <strong>added sugar</strong> rather
                than total sugar.
              </p>

              <h2>Typical sugar content of common foods &amp; drinks</h2>
              <p>
