              <h2>Health risks of too much added sugar</h2>
              <p>
                Regularly exceeding your added sugar limit is linked with a
                higher risk of:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Weight gain and obesity</strong> – sugary drinks are
                  easy to overconsume and don’t make you feel full.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Type 2 diabetes</strong> – especially when combined
                  with excess calories and low activity.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease</strong> – high
                  intakes of fructose from sugary drinks can burden the liver.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Heart disease</strong> – high sugar intake is
                  associated with higher triglycerides, blood pressure and
                  inflammation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tooth decay</strong> – frequent sugary snacks and
                  drinks feed cavity-causing bacteria.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Cutting back on added sugar is one of the
                <strong>most impactful changes</strong> you can make for
                long-term health, especially if most of your sugar comes from
                drinks.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips to reduce added sugar</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Swap
                  <strong
                    >sugary drinks for water, sparkling water or unsweetened
                    tea</strong
                  >
                  most of the time.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Choose <strong>plain yogurt</strong> and add fruit instead of
                  buying sweetened versions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Gradually <strong>reduce sugar in coffee or tea</strong> – for
                  example, cut by ¼ teaspoon every week.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Check labels for <strong>“added sugars”</strong> and compare
                  brands; choose lower-sugar options.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Keep sweets as <strong>occasional treats</strong>, not
                  everyday staples.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Focus on <strong>whole foods</strong> – vegetables, fruit,
                  whole grains, nuts, seeds, lean proteins.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and medical disclaimer</h2>
              <p>
                This sugar intake calculator is for
                <strong>education and general guidance only</strong>. It:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Uses simplified formulas and typical values, not a full
                  clinical nutrition assessment.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not account for specific medical conditions, medications
                  or pregnancy.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Assumes average body composition for your weight and activity
                  level.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you have
                <strong
                  >diabetes, prediabetes, fatty liver disease, high
                  triglycerides, kidney disease</strong
                >
                or any other health condition, talk to your doctor or a
                registered dietitian before making major dietary changes.
              </p>
