              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >How much sugar per day is OK?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    For most adults, keeping
                    <strong>added sugar below 10% of daily calories</strong> is
                    considered acceptable, and below 5% is even better. That’s
                    roughly <strong>25–50 g per day</strong> (6–12 teaspoons)
                    for many people. Our calculator personalizes this range
                    based on your weight, age, activity level and health goal.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >Does fruit sugar count toward my limit?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Whole fruits contain natural sugars, but they also provide
                    fiber, vitamins and antioxidants. Most guidelines focus on
                    <strong>added sugar</strong>, not sugar naturally present in
                    whole fruit. If you eat a lot of fruit juice or smoothies,
                    those can behave more like sugary drinks and may be worth
                    tracking.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
